how to delete all commit history in git

If you want to delete all commit history in Git and keep only the latest code, you need to create a new orphan branch and push it to overwrite the repository history.

⚠️ Warning: This permanently removes all previous commits from the repository history.

Method: Remove All Git Commit History
1️⃣ Go to your repository
cd your-repository
2️⃣ Create a new orphan branch

This creates a branch without any commit history.

git checkout --orphan latest_branch
3️⃣ Add all files
git add -A
4️⃣ Create a new commit
git commit -m "Initial commit"

Now your repo contains only one commit.

5️⃣ Delete old main branch
git branch -D main

If your branch is master, use:

git branch -D master
6️⃣ Rename the new branch
git branch -m main
7️⃣ Force push to GitHub
git push -f origin main

This overwrites the remote history.

Verify

Run:

git log

You should see only one commit.

Alternative (Fast Method)

Delete .git and reinitialize:

rm -rf .git
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git remote add origin <repo-url>
git push -f origin main
When this is used

Removing sensitive data from history

Cleaning huge commit history

Resetting repo before open source release

Fixing GitHub secret scanning issues

